snippet.textDisplay: Considering the 32 core version is going for $2000 now, I'm guessing at least $3000 unless they adjust their price points. Intel Xeon who again? Actually, I'm wondering what AMD is going to be doing with their own Epyc line since the 32 core Threadripper is getting pretty close to the same performance as the 64 core Epyc. Granted Epyc allows multiple CPU's on a single motherboard, but how hard would that be to just include in Threadripper and merge the two lines? As for who wants one at the consumer level? If I had the funds to throw at a PC, I'd gladly build a system around one. It would be great for running multiple virtual machines and some other applications that I actually am interested in.v
